<br />
<br />I think this is mostly why.. it's a huge up-front investment and a risk, but almost everyone would balk at the price it would have to sell for to break even (even though the parts get cheaper, it will never be 'cheap enough' to compete with the clones available now).  I've seen lots of people complain about the price of the PowerPak (which seems like a fair price to me), but imagine how much more they would complain if there was a Chinese clone of it that sold for $15, and the only downside is some inaccuracies that most of the people using it wouldn't even be looking for.  Almost no one would buy the PowerPak then, and I imagine a system clone would go the same way.

		

